Dopamine transporter density in
patients with attention deficit
hyperactivity disorder
Darin D Dougherty, Ali A Bonab, Thomas J Spencer,
Scott L Rauch, Bertha K Madras, Alan J Fischman
Dopamine transporter density was measured in vivo in six adult
patients with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. We have
shown a 70% increase in age-corrected dopamine transporter
density in patients with attention hyperactivity disorder
compared with healthy controls.
Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) affects
between 3 and 5% of children in the USA1 and in many cases
continues into adolescence and adulthood. Despite the high
frequency and seriousness of ADHD, little information is
currently available about its causes and pathophysiology.
Because of the central role of dopamine in psychomotor
activity and reward seeking behaviour, several molecular
genetic studies of ADHD have concentrated on genes
involved in dopaminergic function.2 Specifically, associations
of both the dopamine D4 receptor gene and the dopamine
transporter gene (DAT1) with ADHD have been described.3
Association of the dopamine transporter with ADHD is of
particular importance because this site is the main target for
medications, such as methylphenidate, pemoline, and
dexamphetamine which are the treatments of choice for
ADHD. Since a positive correlation between expression of
DAT1 alleles and hyperactivity-impulsivity score has been
shown4 we postulated that ADHD may be caused by over
expression of DAT. To address this issue, we measured DAT
density by single photon emission computed tomography
(SPECT) with the highly selective radiopharmaceutical
iodine-123-labelled altropane.5
Six adult patients with ADHD (four women; age 24–51
years, mean [SD] 41·33 [4·46]) participated in the study and
the results were compared with a database of 30 healthy
