The phantom of progressive
dementia in epilepsy
C Helmstaedter, C E Elger
Age regression measures of memory in patients with epilepsy
show that increased incidence of amnesia/dementia is not the
consequence of progressive epilepsy.
Chronic pharmacoresistant epilepsy is a very harmful disease
which, besides all risks directly associated with uncontrolled
seizures, is still believed to be accompanied by progressive
mental deterioration. Such deterioration is of particular
interest in patients with epilepsies of the mesiotemporal
structures, 
which are 
essential 
for 
human 
memory
processing.1,2
In 
these 
patients, 
bilateral 
damage 
of
mesiotemporal structures can lead to severe anterograde
amnesia, and make long-term consolidation of newly
acquired information nearly impossible. Although mesial
pathology in temporal-lobe epilepsy is mostly unilateral, there
may be deterioration of memory functions due to progression
of the disease, or secondary physiological or structural
changes as a consequence of seizures, injuries, antiepileptic
medication, and so on. Finally, interactions of mesial
pathology with physiological ageing must be considered since
these interactions may lead to deteriorating memory at an
advanced age. Stimulated by findings in operated and non-
operated 
patients 
with 
temporal-lobe 
epilepsy,3,4
we
investigated the interactions of mesial pathology with
physiological ageing more closely in a cross-sectional study in
a clinically homogeneous group of 63 patients with chronic
pharmacoresistant left mesial temporal-lobe epilepsy and
hippocampal sclerosis.
All patients were candidates for epilepsy surgery, and the
cognitive data reported here were collected before surgery.
There were 34 men and 29 women. The mean onset of
epilepsy was early (mean age 10 years [SD 7]) and the mean
age at investigation was 33 years (9; range 12–51) with the
mean duration of epilepsy being 23 years (11; 1–49). Seven
patients were left handed, four ambidextrous. According to
non-invasive (dichotic listening) or invasive (Wada test in 23
patients) examinations, all 63 patients were assumed to be left
hemisphere language dominant. A group of 125 healthy
people matched for age and sex served as a control group. We
assessed episodic memory by verbal word list learning which
includes serial learning, delayed free recall, and a recognition
trial. Also, as a control condition, we assessed semantic
knowledge by means of a passive vocabulary-intelligence test,
which requires the recognition of words with increasing
difficulty (decreasing frequency of occurrence) out of several
options. We calculated correlations between the per-
formances on each test in addition to group differences, and
we also assessed age effects on both performances, since
episodic memory is known to deteriorate with advanced age. 
The performances on each test, of patients with mesial
temporal-lobe epilepsy and healthy controls, showed the
same significant divergent development with increasing age:
vocabulary increased and verbal learning, memory, and
recognition decreased (figure). Age regressions were the same
in both groups. However, patients with temporal-lobe
epilepsy had significant difficulties with learning, retrieval,
and recognition of the word list (standard values <1 SD), but
not with vocabulary (standard values >1 SD) (table). No
measure of episodic memory correlated with performance in
vocabulary in either group. Since age regression of memory is
very much the same in patients and in healthy individuals, no
accelerated deterioration of memory, due to progression of
the disease or a longer duration of epilepsy, can be
concluded. Nevertheless, an increased frequency of amnestic
patients can be expected with advanced age because there is
evidence of an additive effect of pre-existing disease and
physiological ageing. Furthermore, semantic knowledge is not
impaired and gains in knowledge can still be achieved despite
impaired and deteriorating episodic memory. This finding
accords with suggestions on age-dependent fluent intelligence
and age-independent crystalline intelligence, and with current
